## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()`** — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()`** — also removed; no equivalent exists
3. The entire abort-based cancellation model is gone by design (it was always unsafe — could corrupt state mid-execution)

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, respecting the timeout.
            // If the task hasn't started yet, cts cancels the scheduling.
            // If it's running, we still throw on timeout.
            task.Wait(timeout);
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is not null)
        {
            // Unwrap and rethrow the real exception
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerExceptions);
        }

        if (!task.IsCompleted)
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");

        // Propagate any exception thrown inside the delegate
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
}
```

### If `work` supports cancellation (preferred)

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, there is **no way** to forcibly kill a running task in .NET 8. If `work` ignores the `CancellationToken`, it runs to completion even after timeout. This is by design — forced aborts corrupted state. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | In the first variant, a timed-out task keeps running in the background. If `work` holds resources (DB connections, file handles), they won't be released until it finishes. |
| **`Task.Wait` vs `await`** | The synchronous version blocks a thread pool thread. Prefer `async` if your callers support it: `await Task.Run(...).WaitAsync(timeout)` (.NET 6+). |
| **`default(T)` race** | The original code had a subtle race — `result` could be read before the thread wrote it. `Task<T>` eliminates this entirely. |

### Async version (best practice for .NET 8)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                         .WaitAsync(timeout);  // .NET 6+ API
    }
    catch (TimeoutException)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

**Bottom line:** The old pattern relied on `Thread.Abort()` which was always unsafe. The .NET 8 approach requires **cooperative cancellation** — your `work` delegate must check `CancellationToken` to actually stop. There is no substitute for forced thread termination, and that's intentional.
